'''Analia Saban''' (b. 1980 in [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]]) is a contemporary conceptual artist based in [[Los Angeles]] and [[New York City]]. Her work takes traditional artistic media such as  [[drawing]], [[painting]] and [[sculpture]] and pushes their limits as a scientific experimentation with art making. 

== Biography ==
Analia Saban grew up in Buenos Aires, hailing from intellectual European heritage. She always sort of knew that she wanted to be an artist. "This is what I was born to do,” she says.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tmagazine.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/02/26/analia-saban-artist-argentina/|title=In Analia Saban's Unassuming Artwork, More Than Meets the Eye|last=Baumgardner|first=Julie|date=2015-02-26|website=T Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref> Saban earned her B.F.A in Visual Arts from [[Loyola University New Orleans]] and her M.F.A in New Genres from [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]].<ref name="subconscious">{{cite news |last=Green |first=Allison |url= http://www.flaunt.com/content/art/analia-saban-reflections-issue-feature |title=Analia Saban: Let's Let the Subconscious Speak for Itself, Shall We? |work=[[Flaunt]] |date=November 30, 2017 |accessdate=March 1, 2019}}</ref> She studied under the artist [[John Baldessari]] and now works in his former Santa Monica studio.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/30/arts/design/an-artist-at-home-on-the-fault-lines.html|title=An Artist at Home on the Fault Lines|last=Finkel|first=Jori|date=2017-06-30|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>

==Work==
Saban often works with materials in ways that confuse or subvert their typical meaning or use in studio art practice. She describes her method of working as artistic, scientific, and archeological,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artsy.net/artist/analia-saban|title=Analia Saban - 113 Artworks, Bio & Shows on Artsy|website=www.artsy.net|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>due to her awareness of the larger social implications of her material and object-based inquiries. Of her work, Saban has said "I like to work as unconsciously as I can, letting ideas take over my production. I try to avoid “forcing” the creative process. I try to keep a constant level of experimentation, but sometimes I also have to sit, look at previous work, or experiments, or the empty wall, and wait.."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/tracey-harnish/artist-analia-saban_b_1484083.html|title=Analia Saban|date=|publisher=Huffington Post|accessdate=2014-04-23}}</ref> She seeks to redefine the traditional notions of painting by utilizing the medium of paint as the subject of her work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tanyabonakdargallery.com/artists/analia-saban/series-works_1|title=Analia Saban|last=|first=|date=2015|website=Tanya Bonakdar Gallery|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=March 13, 2019}}</ref> 

Some of Saban's more well known projects have involved completely unraveling a painted canvas and re-weaving the threads into scarves or rolling them into a "Painting Ball,"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/exhibitions/analia-saban-grinds-down-car-lacquer-minerals-and-insects-for-paintings-1044791|title=Analia Saban Bends Marble and Grinds Car Paint for Her Artworks|date=2017-08-10|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> bending slabs of marble or concrete and draping them over sawhorses,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/exhibitions/analia-saban-grinds-down-car-lacquer-minerals-and-insects-for-paintings-1044791|title=Analia Saban Bends Marble and Grinds Car Paint for Her Artworks|date=2017-08-10|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> and printing plastic bags out of hand-made cotton paper.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artsy.net/show/mixografia-analia-saban-paper-or-plastic|title=Analia Saban: Paper or Plastic? {{!}} Mixografia {{!}} Artsy|website=www.artsy.net|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>

She is the winner of the Norton Museum's 2012 "Rudin Prize For Emerging Photographers".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tanyabonakdargallery.com/exhibitions/2012-rudin-prize-for-emerging-photographers|title=2012 Rudin Prize for Emerging Photographers - Exhibitions - Tanya Bonakdar Gallery|website=www.tanyabonakdargallery.com|access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref>  

Saban's work has been exhibited widely both nationally and internationally and are represented in the  collections of the Allen Memorial Art Museum of Oberlin College, the Hessel Museum of Art at Bard College, the Hammer Museum at UCLA in Los Angeles, Museum of Contemporary Art in Los Angeles, Norton Museum of Art in Florida, and Los Angeles County Museum of Art.

